WEBVTT

00:00:00.300 --> 00:00:07.900
What if a demo video was not a recording you capture, but a value you compile? This is DemoCreate.

00:00:07.900 --> 00:00:19.900
One declarative artifact — describing a codebase or a research paper — compiles through a deterministic pipeline into a verified, provenance-signed video. Here is the whole idea on one screen.

00:00:19.900 --> 00:00:29.100
A demo is a declarative spine: scenes of narration chunks, each an ordered stream of typed actions. Three ideas carry the whole system.

00:00:29.100 --> 00:00:37.900
The spine is plain data. A demo is scenes; a scene is chunks; a chunk is typed actions. Rendering never mutates it.

00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:54.300
Every capability hides behind an interface with a deterministic default. Silent gives you zero dependencies; the system voice is a real OS binary; and a wired Kokoro neural voice — the very voice narrating this video — is a fully-local upgrade.

00:00:54.300 --> 00:01:06.300
Timing is measured, never guessed. We synthesize the narration, measure its real duration, transcribe it back to word timestamps, and anchor each action to the word it is spoken on.

00:01:06.300 --> 00:01:14.700
Everything you are watching is generated from that spine. The code you just saw typed itself in. Look at this frame.

00:01:14.700 --> 00:01:24.300
One commented YAML controls the whole look and sound — five built-in themes, any aspect ratio, resolution up to four K, and near-lossless quality.

00:01:24.300 --> 00:01:37.100
The same engine demos a research paper: it reads the PDF with no Python dependency, recovers the real abstract, the real figure captions, and the sections — and shows each figure whole.

00:01:37.100 --> 00:01:50.300
And it does not only describe itself. Point it at a folder of repositories and it renders one narrated, content-verified video per project — each read from that project's own README and docstrings.

00:01:50.300 --> 00:02:00.300
Under the hood, eight subsystems compose: the spine flows into narration, then rendering, then export — every stage a pure function of the one artifact.

00:02:00.300 --> 00:02:10.700
And it is real. Six hundred ninety one collected tests, seven subsystems, five themes, four K output — and zero binary dependencies for the core path.

00:02:10.700 --> 00:02:19.100
Every render carries its own provenance, three ways — so a video can prove where it came from, and resist tampering.

00:02:19.100 --> 00:02:28.700
Then one command renders a high-definition video with a real neural voiceover, and proves it is genuine — real streams, not silent, not black.

00:02:28.700 --> 00:02:37.500
Declarative. Deterministic. Dogfooded. This entire video was compiled by DemoCreate from one file. Edit it, re-render, and never record a take again.
